sentences: Gryce and the other personnel from the Hampton Band returned to New York in November 1953, where the hard bop scene was just beginning to gain traction.
Gryce formed a quintet with Farmer in March 1954, which first recorded for Prestige Records in May of that year.
The record made in May 1955 by the Farmer-Gryce quintet featured pianist Freddie Redd, bassist Addison Farmer, and drummer Art Taylor.

Later in 1955 Gryce also played for Oscar Pettiford's octet, and got the opportunity to play alto in Thelonious Monk's session with Percy Heath and Art Blakey for Signal Records (released as one side of Gryce's 1955 album, best known under the title Nica's Tempo) .
The final ticket to Gryce's success was his third recording with the Farmer Quintet in October 1955 and his nonet recordings for Signal Records immediately after.
In 1955 he started his own publishing company, Melotone Music, and later an additional company called Totem.

He put together his own quintet, which he renamed the Orch-tette after adding vibraphonist Eddie Costa in 1960.
Gryce worked on a handful of other projects in 1960, including a film score to On the Sound by Phil Baker and a final studio recording on Randy Weston's Uhuru Afrika.
Around 1963, Gryce withdrew completely from his jazz career.
Gryce is known to have had two romantic relationships before his marriage to Eleanor Sears in 1953.

At the Boston Conservatory in 1953 he named one of his symphonies "Gashiya" for a surah in the Qur'an.
He dissolved his publishing companies in 1963 and gave up his music career, thereafter adopting his Islamic name entirely, Basheer Qusim.
In the 1960s Gryce reinvented himself as a public school teacher in New York.
He received a master's degree in education from Fordham University in 1978 and developed an incredible passion for teaching.
Gryce died on March 14, 1983, of a heart attack after becoming increasingly ill.

Little is known about Gryce's financial troubles in the early 1960s, but this hardship very much contributed to Gryce's breakdown and withdrawal from the jazz community.

Gryce revealed very little about his business hardships, but what is known is that his publishing business encountered financial troubles in the early 1960s, with many musicians withdrawing from Melotone and Totem.
The years 1957 to 1960 saw a series of miscellaneous projects for Gryce.
He also began to explore the New York scene, where he would eventually find himself in the early fifties.

The early thirties saw tragedy and hardship for the Gryce family.
